│ stop({"edit_points": [[2061, 2071, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe assertion failure  │
│ occurs in `VPTransformState::get()` when trying to access a scalar value for a VPValue that is marked as `onlyFirstLaneUsed` but has multiple scalars     │
│ stored in `Data.VPV2Scalars[Def]`. The assertion checks that if a value is only used in the first lane, then it should have exactly one scalar value      │
│ stored (for lane 0).\n\nFrom the debugger output, we confirmed:\n- `vputils::onlyFirstLaneUsed(Def)` returns `true`\n- `Data.VPV2Scalars[Def].size()`     │
│ returns `4` (which equals the vectorization factor)\n\nThis indicates that the VPValue is being treated as if it should only use the first lane, but      │
│ multiple scalar instances have been created for all lanes.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n\nThe debug log shows that the loop vectorizer is creating       │
│ multiple replicated blocks for the `udiv` instruction (`pred.udiv.if`, `pred.udiv.if1`, `pred.udiv.if3`, etc.), each containing a scalar `udiv`           │
│ instruction. This suggests that the `udiv` instruction is being replicated for each lane of the vector, even though it should only be needed in the first │
│ lane.\n\nThe issue occurs when a `VPBlendRecipe` tries to access the VPValue (which represents the `udiv` result) and expects only a single scalar value  │
│ since `onlyFirstLaneUsed` returns true.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe root cause is in the `VPReplicateRecipe::shouldPack()` method. This method      │
│ determines whether a replicated recipe should pack its scalar values into a vector. The current logic checks if the recipe is used by a                   │
│ `VPPredInstPHIRecipe` which in turn is used by a non-scalar user.\n\nHowever, there's a flaw in this logic. When a value is `onlyFirstLaneUsed`, it       │
│ should NOT be packed into a vector with multiple lanes, because only the first lane is actually used. The current `shouldPack()` implementation doesn't   │
│ consider the `onlyFirstLaneUsed` property of the VPValue.\n\nIn our reproducer, the `udiv` instruction produces a value that is only used by a phi node   │
│ in the `loop.latch` block, and this phi node only uses the first lane (since the other path provides a constant 0). However, because of the predication   │
│ structure, `shouldPack()` returns true, causing the `VPReplicateRecipe::execute()` to pack all 4 scalar instances into a vector. Later, when the          │
│ `VPBlendRecipe` tries to access this value with `OnlyFirstLaneUsed=true`, it expects only one scalar but finds 4, triggering the assertion.\n\n4.         │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to modify `VPReplicateRecipe::shouldPack()` to return false when the recipe's result is only used in the first      │
│ lane. This prevents unnecessary packing of scalar values that should remain as single scalars.\n\n+ Edit point in                                         │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp` lines 2061-2071:\n  The `shouldPack()` method should check if the recipe's defined value is only used in │
│ the first lane, and if so, return false to avoid packing multiple scalars.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nBy modifying `VPReplicateRecipe::shouldPack()` to respect │
│ the `onlyFirstLaneUsed` property, we prevent the creation of multiple scalar instances for values that are only needed in the first lane. This ensures    │
│ that the assertion in `VPTransformState::get()` is satisfied, as values marked as `onlyFirstLaneUsed` will indeed have only one scalar value stored. This │
│ fix addresses the root cause while maintaining the correct behavior for cases where packing is actually needed."})                                        │
